  "local_port": 59970,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Where can I find a training data set (free or not) for patent/prior art search to train a deep learning engine to select relevant prior art/ patents?",
  "response": "Training a deep learning engine for patent and prior art search requires access to comprehensive and well-structured datasets. Below are several resources, both free and paid, where you can obtain patent data suitable for training such models. Additionally, I provide some guidance on how to approach prior art datasets.\n\n### **Free Resources**\n\n1. **United States Patent and Trademark Office (USPTO)**\n   - **USPTO Bulk Data Downloads:** The USPTO provides bulk patent data downloads, including full-text patents, metadata, and patent classifications.\n     - **Link:** [USPTO Bulk Data](https://www.uspto.gov/learning-and-resources/open-data-and-mobility/open-government-data)\n   - **Patent Public Search:** An interactive search tool to access USPTO's full-text patent data.\n     - **Link:** [Patent Public Search](https://ppubs.uspto.gov/pubwebapp/static/pages/landing.html)\n\n2. **European Patent Office (EPO)**\n   - **Open Patent Services (OPS):** APIs that provide programmatic access to EPO\u2019s patent data, including bibliographic data, full-text, and legal status.\n     - **Link:** [EPO OPS](https://www.epo.org/searching-for-patents/data/web-services/ops.html)\n   - **Espacenet:** A free service that offers access to over 120 million patent documents worldwide.\n     - **Link:** [Espacenet](https://worldwide.espacenet.com/)\n\n3. **Google Patents Public Datasets**\n   - **BigQuery Patent Data:** Google provides a comprehensive patent dataset on Google BigQuery, which includes patents from the USPTO and EPO.\n     - **Link:** [Google BigQuery Public Datasets](https://cloud.google.com/bigquery/public-data/google-patents)\n\n4. **The Lens**\n   - A free tool offering access to global patent data and scholarly works, which can be useful for prior art searches.\n     - **Link:** [The Lens](https://www.lens.org/)\n\n5. **Kaggle Datasets**\n   - **Semiconductor Patent Classification:** Example of a patent-related dataset available on Kaggle.\n     - **Link:** [Kaggle Datasets](https://www.kaggle.com/datasets)\n\n6. **PatentScope by WIPO**\n   - Provides access to international Patent Cooperation Treaty (PCT) applications in full text format.\n     - **Link:** [PatentScope](https://patentscope.wipo.int/)\n\n### **Paid Resources**\n\n1. **Derwent Innovation by Clarivate**\n   - Offers enriched patent data with detailed indexing and categorization, which can enhance model training.\n     - **Link:** [Derwent Innovation](https://clarivate.com/products/derwent-innovation/)\n\n2. **LexisNexis TotalPatent One**\n   - Provides comprehensive patent data with advanced search and analytics capabilities.\n     - **Link:** [TotalPatent One](https://www.lexisnexis.com/en-us/products/totalpatent-one.page)\n\n3. **PatSnap**\n   - A commercial platform offering extensive patent data, analytics, and visualization tools.\n     - **Link:** [PatSnap](https://www.patsnap.com/)\n\n4. **Elsevier's Derwent World Patents Index (DWPI)**\n   - A curated dataset with high-quality patent data suitable for advanced analytics.\n     - **Link:** [DWPI](https://www.clarivate.com/products/scientific-and-academic-research/research-discovery-and-analytics/derwent-world-patents-index/)\n\n5. **Data Providers like Ora et Labora**\n   - Offer specialized datasets and custom data services tailored for intellectual property analysis.\n     - **Link:** [Ora et Labora](http://www.ora-et-labora.com/)\n\n### **Prior Art Datasets**\n\n**Prior art** encompasses not only patents but also non-patent literature (NPL) such as academic papers, technical reports, standards, and more. Creating a robust dataset for prior art search may involve aggregating various data sources:\n\n1. **Semantic Scholar**\n   - Access to a vast number of scholarly articles that can serve as non-patent prior art.\n     - **Link:** [Semantic Scholar APIs](https://www.semanticscholar.org/product/api)\n\n2. **arXiv and Other Preprint Repositories**\n   - Access to preprints in various scientific and technical fields.\n     - **Link:** [arXiv API](https://arxiv.org/help/api/index)\n\n3. **Open Access Journals**\n   - Platforms like PLOS, PubMed Central, and others provide access to a wide range of scientific literature.\n     - **Link:** [PubMed Central](https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/)\n\n4. **Technical Standards Organizations**\n   - Sources like IEEE, ISO, and others publish standards that can be considered prior art.\n     - **Links:** \n       - [IEEE Xplore](https://ieeexplore.ieee.org/Xplore/home.jsp)\n       - [ISO Standards](https://www.iso.org/standards.html)\n\n### **Creating Labeled Datasets**\n\nWhile raw patent and prior art data is readily available, labeled datasets specifically curated for relevance classification may be scarce. Here are some approaches to creating your own dataset:\n\n1. **Using Existing Patent Reclassification Tasks:**\n   - Leverage existing datasets used in research for patent classification or semantic similarity tasks.\n   - Example: The *Cited Reference* network can help establish relationships between patents.\n\n2. **Human Annotation:**\n   - Manually label a subset of patent pairs or document pairs for relevance. This process can be time-consuming but ensures high-quality labels.\n\n3. **Semi-Automated Labeling:**\n   - Use citation data (e.g., citations between patents) as a proxy for relevance. Patents citing each other are likely to be relevant.\n\n4. **Crowdsourcing:**\n   - Platforms like Amazon Mechanical Turk can be used to scale the labeling process, though ensuring quality control is essential.\n\n### **Considerations for Training Deep Learning Models**\n\n- **Data Volume and Quality:** Ensure that the dataset is large enough and encompasses diverse patent classes and technologies to train a robust model.\n- **Preprocessing:** Normalize text data, handle patent-specific terminology, and manage different languages if dealing with international patents.\n- **Feature Engineering:** Consider leveraging patent metadata such as classifications (e.g., CPC codes), publication dates, and citation networks.\n- **Evaluation Metrics:** Define appropriate metrics (e.g., precision, recall, F1-score) based on the specific relevance criteria relevant to your application.\n- **Legal Compliance:** Ensure compliance with data usage licenses, especially when using paid datasets or aggregating data from multiple sources.\n\n### **Additional Resources and Tools**\n\n- **Patent NLP Libraries:**\n  - **PatentsView API:** Provides various tools and data for patent analysis.\n    - **Link:** [PatentsView](https://www.patentsview.org/api/)\n  - **spaCy Patent Parser:** An open-source tool for parsing patent text.\n    - **Link:** [spaCy Patent Parser GitHub](https://github.com/Diego999/pyspacy)\n\n- **Research Papers and Benchmarks:**\n  - Reviewing recent academic literature can provide insights into how others have constructed and utilized patent datasets for machine learning tasks.\n\nBy leveraging these resources and strategically preparing your dataset, you can effectively train a deep learning engine tailored for patent and prior art search tasks. Depending on your specific requirements and budget, you might combine multiple sources to create a comprehensive and high-quality training dataset.",
